Title: Stratified functional programs and computational complexity  
Author: Daniel Leivant 
Address: Bloomington, IN 47405  
Affiliation: Computer Science Department Indiana University  
Abstract: Synopsis. We develop two notions of stratified recurrence. The first is predicative recurrence, and is similar to the use of levels in predicative (ramified) analysis. Our definition is related to notions introduced in [Lei90,BC92], but it is conceptually unified and generic to all free algebras, and it can use finite and transfinite levels. We show that the functions generated by finite level predicative recurrence over a free algebra A are obtained already using two levels, and are exactly the functions computable by a register machine over A in time polynomial in the syntactic height of the input. For the algebra W of words over a finite alphabet, these are exactly the poly-time functions. When the medium of computation is the algebra N of unary numerals, then the functions generated by predicative recurrence are exactly the numeric functions computable in polynomial space. These characterizations are purely functionals, and use no special initial functions or bounding conditions. Moreover, in the results for both W and N the polynomial degree corresponds to the number of nestings of recurrence, if only two levels are used, and, more generally, to a certain count that combines recurrence and composition, if all finite levels are used. We further examine the result of introducing an impred-icative ingredient in predicative recurrence, in the guise of level-coercion functions. We show that the nesting count of impredicative recurrence provides a stratification of primitive recursion (over the free algebra in hand). Combining this with our predicative stratification, we obtain a purely functional classification of the primitive recursive functions, which for numeric functions is identical to Grzegorczyk's hierarchy from level 3 and up, and which separates between polynomial and exponential growth of functions (a separation that is lacking in the related functional hierarchy of Axt-Heinermann [Axt65,Hei61]). A related classification of the primitive recursive functions (over a free algebra A) is obtained by extending our pred-icative hierarchy into transfinite levels. 
